O:9:"magpierss":20:{s:6:"parser";i:0;s:12:"current_item";a:0:{}s:5:"items";a:10:{i:0;a:12:{s:5:"title";s:31:"WFS Simple takes a step forward";s:4:"link";s:34:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?p=24";s:8:"comments";s:43:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?p=24#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 21 Apr 2007 14:39:48 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:8:"rajsingh";}s:8:"category";s:15:"georsswfssimple";s:4:"guid";s:34:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?p=24";s:11:"description";s:345:"In the OGC meetings last week WFS Simple was presented to the membership as a part of the &#8220;OWS4 GeoDSS Mass Market (formerly GeoRSS) IPR&#8220;. It was approved as a discussion paper, which is a document that&#8217;s worth making public, but is not necessarily an &#8220;official&#8221; position of the OGC (as a Best Practices paper [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:1868:"<p>In the OGC meetings last week <a href="http://www.ogcnetwork.net/wfssimple">WFS Simple</a> was presented to the membership as a part of the &#8220;<a href="http://portal.opengeospatial.org/files/?artifact_id=20431&amp;version=1">OWS4 GeoDSS Mass Market (formerly GeoRSS) IPR</a>&#8220;. It was approved as a discussion paper, which is a document that&#8217;s worth making public, but is not necessarily an &#8220;official&#8221; position of the OGC (as a Best Practices paper is).</p>
<p>There were two major areas of discussion at the meeting. One was around whether WFS Simple should harmonize with <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/wfs">WFS</a> and become the most basic WFS implementation. The other was related to <a href="http://www.ogcnetwork.net/node/189">Basic XML Feature Schema (BXFS)</a> as the default output schema for WFS Simple. These are actually related items as the biggest problem with rolling WFS Simple into WFS would be the issue of having GML as a required output format.</p>
<p>Although at first blush it sounds nice to bring this work into an existing service, I agree with the opinions that it should stay separate. GML as a required output format is too important of a foundation of WFS to tinker with. Therefore I propose maintaining the separation and pursuing the following work items leading to a 1.0 specification.</p>
<p>1. keep WFS Simple focussed on being the generic geospatial data query language for mainstream web data formats like Atom+GeoRSS, KML, etc.</p>
<p>2. Componentize the design of the service, so that this is not really one service, but a simple, clear way to design services focussed on a particular data type like Atom+GeoRSS by adding or removing a parameter or two.</p>
<p>3. Re-emphasize the separation from WFS by moving towards a 1.0 specification with a new name, Geodata Query Service</p>
";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:44:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?feed=rss2&p=24";}s:7:"summary";s:345:"In the OGC meetings last week WFS Simple was presented to the membership as a part of the &#8220;OWS4 GeoDSS Mass Market (formerly GeoRSS) IPR&#8220;. It was approved as a discussion paper, which is a document that&#8217;s worth making public, but is not necessarily an &#8220;official&#8221; position of the OGC (as a Best Practices paper [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:1868:"<p>In the OGC meetings last week <a href="http://www.ogcnetwork.net/wfssimple">WFS Simple</a> was presented to the membership as a part of the &#8220;<a href="http://portal.opengeospatial.org/files/?artifact_id=20431&amp;version=1">OWS4 GeoDSS Mass Market (formerly GeoRSS) IPR</a>&#8220;. It was approved as a discussion paper, which is a document that&#8217;s worth making public, but is not necessarily an &#8220;official&#8221; position of the OGC (as a Best Practices paper is).</p>
<p>There were two major areas of discussion at the meeting. One was around whether WFS Simple should harmonize with <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/standards/wfs">WFS</a> and become the most basic WFS implementation. The other was related to <a href="http://www.ogcnetwork.net/node/189">Basic XML Feature Schema (BXFS)</a> as the default output schema for WFS Simple. These are actually related items as the biggest problem with rolling WFS Simple into WFS would be the issue of having GML as a required output format.</p>
<p>Although at first blush it sounds nice to bring this work into an existing service, I agree with the opinions that it should stay separate. GML as a required output format is too important of a foundation of WFS to tinker with. Therefore I propose maintaining the separation and pursuing the following work items leading to a 1.0 specification.</p>
<p>1. keep WFS Simple focussed on being the generic geospatial data query language for mainstream web data formats like Atom+GeoRSS, KML, etc.</p>
<p>2. Componentize the design of the service, so that this is not really one service, but a simple, clear way to design services focussed on a particular data type like Atom+GeoRSS by adding or removing a parameter or two.</p>
<p>3. Re-emphasize the separation from WFS by moving towards a 1.0 specification with a new name, Geodata Query Service</p>
