";}i:4;a:12:{s:5:"title";s:33:"OGC is standardizing Google?s KML";s:4:"link";s:34:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?p=18";s:8:"comments";s:43:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?p=18#comments";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 23 Feb 2007 07:14:51 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:8:"rajsingh";}s:8:"category";s:23:"ogcgeogeorssmass market";s:4:"guid";s:34:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?p=18";s:11:"description";s:321:"As many know by now, OGC is working to bring KML into the international standardization process. There&#8217;s a public mailing list for interested parties to discuss what they would like to see in an OGC KML, but I&#8217;d like to spend a second on the legal aspect, which is just as important. Here&#8217;s a post [...]";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:1331:"<p>As many know by now, <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/">OGC</a> is working to bring KML into the international standardization process. There&#8217;s a <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/projects/groups/massmarket">public mailing list</a> for interested parties to discuss what they would like to see in an OGC KML, but I&#8217;d like to spend a second on the legal aspect, which is just as important. Here&#8217;s a post I just made on the <a href="http://lists.eogeo.org/mailman/listinfo/georss">GeoRSS mailing list</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p>And one crucial point that I think a lot of people miss is the legal intellectual property aspect. Bringing KML into OGC isn&#8217;t just about what features end up in that XML format. It&#8217;s just as much about making sure the format is royalty-free to use forever. We all know the Google mantra is &#8220;don&#8217;t be evil&#8221; (and the people I know there completely live up to the mantra), but OGC standardization means you don&#8217;t have to take their word for it.</p>
<p>So by standardizing KML in OGC, even if people don&#8217;t get all the features in there they may like to see, at least you will know you can build innovative applications and information services around KML without fear of getting a cease-and-desist in the mail some day.</p></blockquote>
";}s:3:"wfw";a:1:{s:10:"commentrss";s:44:"http://www.rajsingh.org/blog/?feed=rss2&p=18";}s:7:"summary";s:321:"As many know by now, OGC is working to bring KML into the international standardization process. There&#8217;s a public mailing list for interested parties to discuss what they would like to see in an OGC KML, but I&#8217;d like to spend a second on the legal aspect, which is just as important. Here&#8217;s a post [...]";s:12:"atom_content";s:1331:"<p>As many know by now, <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/">OGC</a> is working to bring KML into the international standardization process. There&#8217;s a <a href="http://www.opengeospatial.org/projects/groups/massmarket">public mailing list</a> for interested parties to discuss what they would like to see in an OGC KML, but I&#8217;d like to spend a second on the legal aspect, which is just as important. Here&#8217;s a post I just made on the <a href="http://lists.eogeo.org/mailman/listinfo/georss">GeoRSS mailing list</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p>And one crucial point that I think a lot of people miss is the legal intellectual property aspect. Bringing KML into OGC isn&#8217;t just about what features end up in that XML format. It&#8217;s just as much about making sure the format is royalty-free to use forever. We all know the Google mantra is &#8220;don&#8217;t be evil&#8221; (and the people I know there completely live up to the mantra), but OGC standardization means you don&#8217;t have to take their word for it.</p>
<p>So by standardizing KML in OGC, even if people don&#8217;t get all the features in there they may like to see, at least you will know you can build innovative applications and information services around KML without fear of getting a cease-and-desist in the mail some day.</p></blockquote>
